# ─── JuiceBox DNS Override ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# This dnsmasq instance is the DNS server for the JuiceBox charger only.
# The charger is configured with a static network config that points
# its DNS to this NAS (@@LOCAL_IP@@). Nothing else on the network is
# affected — the Cox router and all other devices use their own DNS.
#
# Why this exists:
#   The JuiceBox uses Enel X's cloud (device-backend-udp-evos.juice.net:8042)
#   as its UDPC (UDP Client) endpoint. By resolving that hostname to our NAS,
#   we intercept the UDP data stream without needing to modify the charger's
#   UDPC setting on every reboot.
#
# The NAS itself (and all Docker containers) use their own upstream DNS
# (the Cox gateway), so JuicePassProxy's forward path to the real Enel X
#  server is unaffected.
#
# Variables substituted from .env at container start:
#   @@LOCAL_IP@@     — NAS LAN IP (LOCAL_IP in .env)
#   @@JUICEBOX_IP@@  — JuiceBox assigned IP (JUICEBOX_IP in .env)
#   @@GATEWAY_IP@@   — LAN gateway / router IP (GATEWAY_IP in .env)
#   @@NIRVANA_IP@@   — Nirvana heat pump assigned IP (NIRVANA_IP in .env)

# ─── Upstream DNS ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
server=8.8.8.8
server=8.8.4.4

# ─── Local overrides ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Redirect the Enel X UDP server hostname to this NAS so that JuicePassProxy
# intercepts charger telemetry instead of it going straight to the cloud.
address=/device-backend-udp-evos.juice.net/@@LOCAL_IP@@

# Redirect Nirvana heat pump cloud to local proxy on NAS (Phase 2A)
address=/nirvana.iot-endpoint.com/@@LOCAL_IP@@

# ─── DHCP for JuiceBox + Nirvana pump ────────────────────────────────────────
#
# dnsmasq handles DHCP exclusively for these two devices.
# All other devices continue to get DHCP from the Cox router.
#
# Prerequisites:
#   Cox DHCP range changed to .5–.253 — removes .2/.3/.4 from Cox's pool.
#   juicebox-dns must run with network_mode: host to receive DHCP broadcasts.
#   .2 is reserved for future use, .3 = Nirvana, .4 = JuiceBox.
#
# IMPORTANT — JuiceBox has two MACs:
#   Hardware / ZentriOS MAC : 4C:55:CC:14:50:E8  (seen in telnet `get network.mac`)
#   Wi-Fi / DHCP MAC        : 52:D4:F7:14:50:E8  ← this is what appears in DHCP frames
#   dhcp-host MUST use the Wi-Fi MAC or dnsmasq will silently ignore all JuiceBox DHCP.
#
# How the DHCP race is won:
#   dhcp-authoritative means dnsmasq sends DHCPNAK for any IP it's not offering to that MAC.
#   Cox cannot offer .2 or .3 (outside its range), so even if Cox responds first, the
#   device eventually accepts dnsmasq's offer.
#
# Verify: docker logs juicebox-dns | grep -i dhcp
# Expected: DHCPACK(eth0) @@JUICEBOX_IP@@ 52:d4:f7:14:50:e8 JuiceBox-0E8
#           DHCPACK(eth0) @@NIRVANA_IP@@  52:d4:f7:98:06:0a Nirvana-06A

dhcp-range=192.168.0.2,@@JUICEBOX_IP@@,12h
dhcp-host=52:d4:f7:14:50:e8,JuiceBox-0E8,@@JUICEBOX_IP@@,12h
# Nirvana heat pump — Wi-Fi MAC (locally-administered; last 3 octets match label FC:0F:E7:98:06:0A)
dhcp-host=52:d4:f7:98:06:0a,Nirvana-06A,@@NIRVANA_IP@@,12h
dhcp-option=3,@@GATEWAY_IP@@    # default gateway
dhcp-option=6,@@LOCAL_IP@@      # DNS server → our dnsmasq
dhcp-authoritative              # respond immediately, DHCPNAK anything not in our assignments
dhcp-ignore=tag:!known          # silently ignore DHCP from all other MACs

# ─── Housekeeping ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
no-hosts          # ignore /etc/hosts inside the container
no-resolv         # ignore /etc/resolv.conf inside the container (use server= above)
log-queries       # log DNS queries — useful for debugging charger DNS activity
log-dhcp          # log DHCP transactions — useful for verifying JuiceBox gets correct lease
